 to protect the citizens is to......... Post one nicely armed police officer in every home...not giving the citizens a choice...its a must. It is the only best way to assure the safety of the citizens.<br><br>Obviously, Joe and Mary have lost their rights to privacy cause of the armed police officer standing constant post in their home. The End.<br><br>The above example/story is not the best in regards to the current situation. But it gives a nice comparison of rights to privacy vs. imposed security.... I can only hope you understand and that my point of freedom for security is clear.<br><br>Aside from our lesson for today, I would like to address something in regards to your previous posts.... It seems you have some preconceived notions as to my rational. You seem to have formulated the conclusion that I am some anti-governmental anarchist of some sort and that I have hostilities towards authority.<br> Aside from this being greatly unappreciated, it is judgmental. To assume crap like      &quot;Next you will be telling me that &quot;freedom to drive&quot; is taken away from .....&quot; about someone you do not know is to make prejudice assumptions. These assumptions only complicate and fog ones ability to make sound, fair and intelligent dialog.<br><br>Do to the terrorist attack, some feel we needed to give the law enforcement in this nation (FBI - CIA etc) more 'liberty' to pursue terrorist. These new liberties that we have given to them has taken away from us some of our liberties and rights. Are you willing to give up your rights for safety and if so...how much? Once we establish your feelings about this we can move on. <br><br>As for Driving: A ‘privilege’.not a right (although everything about driving is taxpayer funded).<br><br>So... in 'rebuttal' of your accusations of me, I post this reply in complete pointy condescending arrogance. /bow<br><br><br><br> <p><B><font color=#00dd00>Rh</font><font color=#00cc00>ea</font><font color=#00bb00>t